 Person [ https://substack.com/redirect/44ff301a-7621-4378-8012-f6ac8fde90f=
2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Cru=
cially, we believe that this trend is entering into the physical world, mak=
ing previously challenged startup business cases viable. Elliot laid out th=
e case for this trend in biotech in Techbio Taxonomy [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/834fa4f7-d9fd-4887-89e7-bec87d7ce2f5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Similar dynamics are shaking up o=
ther hard categories, as I wrote covered in Decentralization [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/f11c838b-005d-4903-9dec-e50317238761?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. This will lead to new opp=
ortunities for early stage funds.=C2=A0
On the Bits side, we believe that infrastructure companies will capture mos=
t of the value =E2=80=93 whether traditional, AI, or web3 =E2=80=93 as it b=
ecomes ever easier, and therefore more competitive, to build applications. =
Like everyone (which is probably a red flag), we=E2=80=99re excited about A=
I=E2=80=99s potential to change everything, but we=E2=80=99re approaching t=
he space very cautiously for now =E2=80=93 there=E2=80=99s going to be an i=
nvestor bloodbath at the application layer. In web3, we think it=E2=80=99s =
a great time to be investing, as other investors disappear at the same time=
 as infrastructure improves and entrepreneurs are imbued with a renewed app=
reciation that they need to create real value for users and connect with re=
al world assets responsibly. Both AI and web3 will impact both Bits and Ato=
ms =E2=80=93 new infrastructure is needed for a Decentralized [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/f11c838b-005d-4903-9dec-e50317238761?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] world =E2=80=93 and that =
the intersection of AI and web3, while buzzword bingo, will be an interesti=
ng space to watch.=C2=A0
On the Atoms side, we believe that startups will be able to harness new tec=
h and commercialize cutting edge science to both partner and compete with i=
ncumbents for large slices of trillion-plus dollar industries like pharma, =
energy, defense, and education while giving humanity new superpowers.=C2=A0
At the same time, a number of key experience curves are reaching points at =
which Atoms business models are economically feasible. We=E2=80=99ve covere=
d these before:=C2=A0
The cost of sequencing the full human genome has dropped from $3 billion to=
 $100.
The cost to send a kilogram to space will reach sub-$50 with the impending =
launch of SpaceX=E2=80=99s Starship, down from $177,900 in 1965.=C2=A0
The cost of a kWh of solar energy [ https://substack.com/redirect/5e4d40f2-=
3637-4353-8f4e-e04b2107d759?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] plummeted from $0.42 in 2009 to $0.05 in 2021, from t=
he most expensive energy source to second cheapest, tied with hydropower, a=
fter wind.
Huang=E2=80=99s Law in GPUs seems to be picking up where Moore=E2=80=99s La=
w left off.=C2=A0
The price of a lithium-ion battery in kWh fell 97%, from $7,523 when I was =
in Pre-K in 1991 to $181 in 2018.=C2=A0
Cheaper energy, intelligence, and infrastructure will make previously impos=
sible things possible, and previously uneconomical things economical.=C2=A0
Of course, Hard Startups are hard. One of the most frequent pieces of pushb=
ack I=E2=80=99ve gotten from LPs I=E2=80=99ve spoken to about Fund III has =
been around the investment dynamics of Hard Startups. It=E2=80=99s true tha=
t they=E2=80=99ve historically been challenging, especially for smaller fun=
ds, but we see the facts on the ground changing, and therefore see this ret=
icence as an opportunity.
We=E2=80=99ve backed a number of companies in traditionally capital-intensi=
ve categories with the ability to scale in a capital efficient manner. As o=
ne example from our Fund II portfolio, Wander [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/3ed759f5-b9af-4e25-8c20-ed2c038a4304?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which is a vertically integrated vacatio=
n rental home company, just launched Atlas [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
cd83f9dc-5619-4930-8fbb-d65d8a8c822d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the =E2=80=9Cworld=E2=80=99s first vacation=
 rental REIT,=E2=80=9D to scale its portfolio without dilutive venture fund=
ing. Fund III biotech companies are doing work with AI that would have take=
n dozens of scientists years to complete, if they could complete it at all.=
=C2=A0
Thanks to declining cost structures and new business models, we believe tha=
t this is the right moment in time for a fund like ours to invest in these =
categories.
To outperform, you need to believe something that others don=E2=80=99t and =
act on that belief. That=E2=80=99s=C2=A0 easy to say and harder to do, beca=
use those beliefs often seem dumb in the moment.=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s my dumb belief: the value of top startups will be higher wit=
hin the life of this fund than they were at the peak in 2021, but the makeu=
p of the list will look very different. Less B2B SaaS, more Moonshots.=C2=
=A0
Of course, there=E2=80=99s a lot of nuance here: each company is different,=
 not all are pursuing capital efficient models, and sometimes, hard startup=
s really are just hard. I=E2=80=99m happy to discuss in more depth with int=
erested LPs [ https://substack.com/redirect/f59712a8-3d05-4380-a66c-9f48bce=
6f0ae?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=
=C2=A0
If you agree now is a good time to invest in Hard Startups, read on. The qu=
estion is: can we invest in those top startups?
Advantage: Deal Flow, Picking, Allocation, and Value Add
In that 8 Mile section, I listed =E2=80=9CCreator GP=E2=80=9D as one of the=
 potential knocks against me. In the bull market, seemingly everyone with a=
n audience and a passing interest in startups launched a fund. LPs have pre=
dictably soured on this subset of GPs and rightly wonder whether they=E2=80=
=99ll stick around. Most won=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
I don=E2=80=99t particularly like the term Creator GP, but I=E2=80=99ll say=
 two things:
Not Boring Capital plans to be around for a very long time, through good ma=
rkets and bad.=C2=A0
This newsletter is our greatest competitive advantage, and I think one of t=
he more differentiated in venture. Importantly, it=E2=80=99s about narrativ=
e, not eyeballs.=C2=A0
All of it comes together in the Not Boring Flywheel, which Jake Singer [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/fbed349f-332e-46c5-a590-99a2a1f69628?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] first wrote abou=
t in Million Dollar Newsletter [ https://substack.com/redirect/937e2982-7fb=
8-4a9a-b4c2-684730c0396b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], when there were only 35,000 of us reading this.=C2=A0
Today, there are over 181,000 of us here, the Flywheel has only gotten stro=
nger, and it can only be enhanced by more tightly coupling the types of com=
panies we invest in and write about with our mission. All of it is in servi=
ce of helping portfolio companies succeed, pre-credit for which shows up in=
 our deal flow, picking, allocation, and value add. All four are intertwine=
d, but I=E2=80=99ll try to break them apart.=C2=A0
Deal Flow. By writing about the categories and ideas we=E2=80=99re most exc=
ited about, we put out a Bat Signal to founders building in those categorie=
s that we=E2=80=99re interested in their space, have thought a lot about it=
, and have a unique perspective to add.=C2=A0
We first met Melonfrost [ https://substack.com/redirect/8c7822a6-1970-4b0b-=
a6f4-53a350b62817?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ] (Fund III), for example, when Sam reached out after reading Ell=
iot=E2=80=99s piece on Ginkgo Bioworks [ https://substack.com/redirect/7dfa=
7cdc-5951-482e-ad17-74f94458d7a4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. A large percentage of the founders in our portf=
olio were Not Boring readers before we invested.
Picking. Spending hours every week thinking deeply about the companies and =
industries we write about, talking to smart people, and getting feedback sh=
arpens our thinking and helps us connect threads.
Asking ourselves about whether we=E2=80=99d want to write about a company i=
s also a good filter for what matters and what people will find useful, and=
 I think that=E2=80=99s informed our picking ability.=C2=A0
As we concentrate and write Deep Dives on all of our Core Fund III investme=
nts, this filter will get even tighter: do we want to spend a week or more =
of our lives heads down writing about this company? If we do, will our read=
ers care about them? Particularly with a more concentrated fund, choosing w=
hat not to invest in is as important as choosing what to invest in.
Allocation. The clarity of the newsletter value proposition helps us win bi=
gger allocations. In Fund I, our average check size was $101,019. One of th=
e questions we had going into Fund II was whether we=E2=80=99d be able to s=
cale that, and we did: the average check size in Fund II was $207,424.=C2=
=A0
For Fund III, we want to scale that again by writing $500k to $1 million ch=
ecks in our Core investments and following on in the winners. There=E2=80=
=99s proof that we can do this. In Fund II, we wrote $500k-$1M checks in 17=
 companies like Vana, Ramp, ScienceIO, Varda, Primer, Series, Nucleus, and =
Composer. There=E2=80=99s a theme here: we=E2=80=99ve written about four of=
 the companies I listed, and plan to write about all of the rest when the t=
iming is right for them.=C2=A0
One of the reasons that we=E2=80=99re going more concentrated in Fund III =
=E2=80=93 beyond fund math =E2=80=93 is that we can get bigger allocations =
in better companies when we write about them.
Value Add. Our advantage in seeing great deals and winning allocations typi=
cally comes from the expectation that we will ultimately be able to add val=
ue. The most straightforward way that we do that is by writing deep dives o=
n companies.=C2=A0
My favorite example of the impact of a deep dive is this tweet from Will Ma=
nidis [ https://substack.com/redirect/6d05a660-68b2-46da-967f-20749bf8329c?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] a coup=
le of months after we wrote about ScienceIO [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/7858ebca-a270-419a-be04-94fe3e653b7d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in The Model of Everything [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/2eb97095-6f51-4a2c-8168-1f3011a99a7a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:
ScienceIO is a Hard Startup, and a complex one to explain, and I think the =
performance of the piece speaks to the fact that we=E2=80=99re at our best =
when we=E2=80=99re explaining those types of companies.=C2=A0
In addition to Deep Dives, we=E2=80=99ve also added the Not Boring Talent C=
ollective, which portfolio companies can use to hire Not Boring readers, an=
d the Not Boring Founders podcast and The Founder=E2=80=99s Letter, which g=
ive our portfolio founders a chance to tell their stories directly. As more=
 of our portfolio companies launch products worth being optimistic about, w=
e can include them in the Weekly Dose of Optimism. Late last year, I launch=
ed Anton Teaches Packy AI with Chroma [ https://substack.com/redirect/c4637=
c89-ee92-4c35-89da-a118418e255e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] CEO Anton Troynikov [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/e6932881-a279-4e14-bee5-9c72c5b49f9d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which helps me learn what=E2=80=99s goin=
g on in AI and gives Chroma some extra visibility.=C2=A0=C2=A0
As we continue to evolve, we=E2=80=99ll keep experimenting with new ways to=
 help our portfolio companies tell their stories, and hopefully, to impact =
their stories in real-time. We=E2=80=99re successful if we give just a litt=
le more leverage to the founders who are trying to bend humanity=E2=80=99s =
trajectory upwards.
Ultimately, we believe we are best-positioned to help those companies tackl=
ing the biggest challenges with the best teams and technology through story=
telling and that they=E2=80=99re the ones that are most aligned with our mi=
ssion.
Approach: Portfolio Construction
Our Fund III approach to portfolio construction is our biggest departure fr=
om Funds I & II.
In Funds I & II, we invested in 207 companies. For Fund III, with more expe=
rience, smarter team members, and bigger ambitions, we=E2=80=99re ready to =
move to a more concentrated strategy.
The Fund will make roughly thirty Core investments from $500k to $1 million=
 (up to $2 million including follow-on rounds), aiming for 1-5% ownership. =
We are not looking to lead rounds; we want to be a valuable 2nd - 4th check=
 in Core companies. We will likely write $500k checks in pre-seeds and seed=
s and $1+ million checks in larger Seeds and Series A=E2=80=99s. We=E2=80=
=99ll invest roughly 50% in Bits and 50% in Atoms.
We will also write a handful of smaller Explore checks in incredibly talent=
ed founders and early stage moonshot ideas, often at the pre-seed and seed.=
 The best of these will graduate to Core investments in Fund III or future =
funds. We=E2=80=99ll reserve 20% of capital to invest in follow-on rounds f=
or our winning companies.
Previously, we had a third category, Growth, but we=E2=80=99re going to be =
focusing earlier stage - Pre-Seed through Series A =E2=80=93 out of Fund II=
I. We will do later stage portfolio company follow-ons and the occasional h=
igh-conviction later stage deals via SPVs, to which LPs will have first acc=
ess.
Of course, this is a riskier strategy than a broader portfolio on paper, bu=
t if we want the chance to earn top decile venture returns, we need to take=
 venture risks.=C2=A0
Ultimately, we=E2=80=99re resetting and doubling down on Not Boring=E2=80=
=99s unique strengths, which we think are particularly well-suited for the =
market to come. Many VCs focus on a particular sector, which can work very =
well if that sector is doing well. We=E2=80=99re more hybrid, which I think=
 makes sense in a market that=E2=80=99s changing as quickly as this one: we=
=E2=80=99re focused on Hard Startups broadly with a horizontal skill set =
=E2=80=93 writing =E2=80=93 and can add depth in the areas we=E2=80=99re mo=
st interested in by adding double-threats like Elliot and Rahul to the team=
=2E=C2=A0
As I=E2=80=99ve written about before, I=E2=80=99m a big fan of differentiat=
ion, even for its own sake, and love a good coherent strategy. An added ben=
efit of our strategy is that our unique advantage is strengthened because t=
here=E2=80=99s no one like us focusing on investing in Hard Startups and he=
lping them tell their stories.=C2=A0
Big funds like Lux, Founders Fund, and a16z=E2=80=99s American Dynamism pra=
ctice are certainly focused on Hard Startups and are excellent lead partner=
s for founders. There are excellent smaller funds focused on many of the sp=
ecific verticals we=E2=80=99re investing in, but few who cover the breadth =
we do. And as far as I know, there aren=E2=80=99t any small, non-lead funds=
 investing in Hard Startups who have storytelling at their core.=C2=A0
But it=E2=80=99s early, and everything above is just words. The proof is in=
 the portfolio.=C2=A0
Fund III Early Portfolio
We began fundraising among existing LPs last year and have started investin=
g out of Fund III, and so far, I=E2=80=99m really excited about the portfol=
io we=E2=80=99re building. It gives a good flavor of the types of companies=
 we=E2=80=99re going to be investing in going forward.=C2=A0
To date, we have invested $2.6 million in nine companies (6 Core, 3 Explore=
) out of Fund III in companies in biotech, web3, energy, and education sinc=
e we began deploying.=C2=A0
Our investments in nxyz, Atomic AI, Melonfrost, Circa, Tlon, Jia, Odyssey, =
and Jaza (the ninth is still in stealth) offer a good flavor of the types o=
f investments we=E2=80=99re making out of this fund:=C2=A0
Hard Startups: Each of the startups we=E2=80=99ve backed is building someth=
ing hard. That might mean that it=E2=80=99s technically difficult (Circa, n=
xyz, and most of our investments), scientifically cutting edge (Atomic AI, =
Melonfrost), requires some legislative schlep (Odyssey, for example), impac=
ts hard-to-impact markets (Jaza, Jia), or requires a business model innovat=
ion (Tlon). If a hacker can build something 50% as good in a weekend, we=E2=
=80=99re not interested. We=E2=80=99re looking for businesses that will bui=
ld deep moats if they succeed, and in many cases, that requires a head star=
t.
Early Stage: All Fund III investments have been at the Pre-Seed, Seed, or S=
eries A, with a concentration at the Seed stage.=C2=A0
So What? Atomic AI will transform the design of RNA-targeted and RNA-based =
medicines to treat currently undruggable diseases. Jaza is bringing power t=
o the 600 million people disconnected from the grid. Jia is filling the $5T=
 developing market credit gap. nxyz is building data and indexing infrastru=
cture that=E2=80=99s critical to a performant web3. Circa is mapping the wo=
rld=E2=80=99s supply chain down to the joule level to strengthen the global=
 supply chain and reduce waste. Tlon is building the operating system for w=
eb3 and a new paradigm for app development. Odyssey is giving parents choic=
e in how they educate their children. Melonfrost is building Evolution-as-a=
-Service so that organism designers can grow anything. If our portfolio doe=
s well, the world does better.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re not building this portfolio specifically to perform in a bear=
 market =E2=80=93 bear markets are temporary, and this one hopefully won=E2=
=80=99t last the 10 year life of the fund =E2=80=93 but an added benefit to=
 investing in companies that are solving problems fundamentally important t=
o people, where no alternatives exist, is that there will be demand in any =
market if they pull it off.
Anyone who invests in Fund III will be investing in these companies that ar=
e already in the portfolio, and hopefully, similarly bold and ambitious one=
s over the next two years.=C2=A0
We have been incredibly selective with our Fund III investments to date and=
 will continue to apply the same high bar going forward.=C2=A0
To Infinity and Beyond
This is the start of a new chapter for Not Boring, one that draws on everyt=
hing we=E2=80=99ve learned so far and everything that gets us so excited ab=
out the future. My goal is for this portfolio to be legendary: I want other=
 investors to talk about our returns in a decade, founders to talk about No=
t Boring=E2=80=99s contributions for years, and our grandkids to still be t=
alking about the impact our companies had in a century.=C2=A0
I feel incredibly lucky to get to write and invest in companies I respect a=
s a living. Thank you for giving me the opportunity to do it. I hope you=E2=
=80=99ll join us.=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99d like to consider becoming an LP in Not Boring Capital, ple=
ase submit your interest here:
It=E2=80=99s not going to be easy, but it=E2=80=99s going to be fun.=C2=A0
Thanks to Dan, Henry, Elliot, Rahul, and Puja for the comments and feedback=
!
Thanks to Dan, Henry, Elliot, Rahul, and Puja for the comments and feedback=
!
That=E2=80=99s all for today! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 with the first Weekly Dose of Optimism in 2023.=20
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

